#### Notes

*   **^** The fee of £8.7s per ton paid to Gorill and Pownall was favorable compared to the average £9.0s per ton demanded by [Thames River](/Thames_River) shipwrights for building 24-gun Royal Navy vessels in the preceding decade. It was also significantly less than the average £9.0s per ton paid for all [Coventry](/Coventry_class)-class vessels constructed in private shipyards between 1756 and 1765.
*   **^** The [Hussar](/HMS_Hussar), [Active](/HMS_Active), and the final vessel in the class, [Hind](/HMS_Hind), were exceptions to the general naming conventions for the [Coventry](/Coventry_class) class.
*   **^** The [Liverpool](/HMS_Liverpool)'s dimensional ratios—3.57:1 for length to breadth, and 3.3:1 for breadth to depth—contrast with standard French equivalents, which could reach up to 3.8:1 and 3:1 respectively. Royal Navy vessels of comparable size and design to the [Liverpool](/HMS_Liverpool) could carry up to 20 [tons](/Long_ton) of powder and shot, whereas French vessels typically carried around 10 tons. They also carried more extensive stores of [rigging](/Rigging), [spars](/Spar_(sailing)), sails, and [cables](/Wire_rope). However, they had fewer ship's boats and less space allocated for the personal effects of the crew.
*   **^** The 29 servants and other ranks included in the ship's complement comprised 20 personal servants and clerical staff, four assistant carpenters, an assistant sailmaker, and the four aforementioned widow's men. Unlike the naval ratings, these individuals did not participate in the sailing or handling of the ship.
*   **^** The [Warren](/USS_Warren) continued to serve as a ship's tender for the [Milford](/HMS_Milford) until December 1776, when she was lost after running aground off [Portsmouth, New Hampshire](/Portsmouth,_New_Hampshire).

